{
  "unit_id": "ch1",
  "title": "Chapter 1 — Basics of Reasoning",
  "skills": [
    {
      "id": "1.1",
      "title": "Claims",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": "1.1-C01",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Welcome to **Claims** — the foundation of arguments."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C02",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "A **claim** is a statement that can be true or false."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C03",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which of these is a claim?",
          "options": [
            "Shut the door!",
            "The sky is blue.",
            "Wow!"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C04",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "All claims are true.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C05",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "A sentence can be a claim even if it's false: 'The moon is made of cheese.'"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C06",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Three common types: **Factual** (what is), **Value** (what's better), **Policy** (what should be done)."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C07",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Classify each statement.",
          "items": [
            "Water boils at 100°C",
            "Vanilla tastes better than chocolate",
            "The city should add bike lanes"
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Factual",
            "Value",
            "Policy"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C08",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Subjective opinions can still be claims if they assert something ('Vanilla tastes better than chocolate')."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C09",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Questions are claims.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C10",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Commands are not claims.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C11",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Non-claims include commands, exclamations, and many questions."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C12",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Pick the **non-claim**.",
          "options": [
            "Please sit down.",
            "Birds have feathers.",
            "Paris is the capital of France."
          ],
          "answer": 0
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C13",
          "type": "fill",
          "prompt": "A claim is something that can be ____ or false.",
          "answer": "true"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C14",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Complex sentences may contain multiple claims; evaluate each clause."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C15",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Edge case: Rhetorical questions can imply claims: 'Isn’t that amazing?' → 'That is amazing.'"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C16",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which contains an implied claim?",
          "options": [
            "Close the window!",
            "Isn’t that dishonest?",
            "Wow!"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C17",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Reports, descriptions, and predictions can all be claims."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C18",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "'It will rain tomorrow' is a claim.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C19",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Classify as Claim / Not-Claim.",
          "items": [
            "Turn the volume down.",
            "Mars has two moons.",
            "Where are my keys?"
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Claim",
            "Not-Claim"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C20",
          "type": "match_pairs",
          "prompt": "Match type to example.",
          "left": [
            "Factual",
            "Value",
            "Policy"
          ],
          "right": [
            "Water freezes at 0°C",
            "Jazz is better than pop",
            "Schools should start later"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C21",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Recap: Claims assert something truth-evaluable. Identify them before evaluating arguments."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C22",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Best definition of a claim?",
          "options": [
            "A sentence that tells someone to act",
            "A sentence that can be true or false",
            "Any sentence with emotion"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C23",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Exclamations like 'Wow!' are claims.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C24",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which pair are both claims?",
          "options": [
            "'Go home.' & 'Where am I?'",
            "'It’s raining.' & 'The streets will be wet.'",
            "'Open the door!' & 'Ouch!'"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C25",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Tip: Ask 'Could this be true or false?' If yes, you likely have a claim."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C26",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which is **not** a claim?",
          "options": [
            "Gravity exists.",
            "Pass the salt.",
            "Dogs are mammals."
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C27",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Opinions cannot be claims.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C28",
          "type": "fill",
          "prompt": "A policy claim often uses the word ______.",
          "answer": "should"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C29",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Classify.",
          "items": [
            "Taxes are too high",
            "Inflation is 3%",
            "We should plant more trees"
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Value",
            "Factual",
            "Policy"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.1-C30",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Great work. You're ready to analyze arguments that use these claims."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "1.2",
      "title": "Arguments",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": "1.2-C01",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Welcome to **Arguments** — not a fight, but a structure of reasoning."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C02",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "An **argument** presents **premises** to support a **conclusion**."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C03",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which best describes an argument?",
          "options": [
            "Two people disagreeing",
            "A set of premises supporting a conclusion",
            "Any opinion"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C04",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Canonical form: Premise 1; Premise 2; ... ∴ Conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C05",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Example:\nP1: All mammals are warm-blooded.\nP2: Whales are mammals.\nC: Therefore, whales are warm-blooded."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C06",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "A single claim is an argument.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C07",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which is an argument?",
          "options": [
            "It's raining.",
            "It's raining, so the streets will be wet.",
            "Rain!"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C08",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Indicator words: 'because', 'since' (premise); 'therefore', 'so', 'thus' (conclusion)."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C09",
          "type": "match_pairs",
          "prompt": "Match indicator to role.",
          "left": [
            "because",
            "since",
            "therefore",
            "thus"
          ],
          "right": [
            "premise",
            "premise",
            "conclusion",
            "conclusion"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C10",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Arguments can be written or spoken; structure matters more than tone."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C11",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Enthymeme: an argument with an implicit premise or conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C12",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "'Socrates is mortal because he is human.' The hidden premise is:",
          "options": [
            "All humans are mortal",
            "All mortals are humans",
            "Socrates is a philosopher"
          ],
          "answer": 0
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C13",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Enthymemes are always invalid.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C14",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Reconstruct arguments by supplying reasonable missing premises."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C15",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Argument vs. Explanation:\n- Argument: why a claim is true.\n- Explanation: why a true claim happened."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C16",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "'The glass broke because it fell.' is:",
          "options": [
            "An argument",
            "An explanation"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C17",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Explanations aim to show *that* something is true.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C18",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Classify as Argument/Not.",
          "items": [
            "I’m tired.",
            "I’m tired because I slept poorly, so I’ll nap."
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Argument",
            "Not-Argument"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C19",
          "type": "fill",
          "prompt": "An argument's reasons are called ______.",
          "answer": "premises"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C20",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Conclusion indicator word:",
          "options": [
            "because",
            "since",
            "therefore"
          ],
          "answer": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C21",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Good reconstruction clarifies structure without changing meaning."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C22",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Pick the conclusion:",
          "options": [
            "All dogs are animals",
            "Fido is a dog",
            "Therefore, Fido is an animal"
          ],
          "answer": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C23",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "'So', 'thus', and 'therefore' often introduce premises.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C24",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Chain arguments: a conclusion of one step becomes a premise for the next."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C25",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Cumulative arguments: multiple independent premises support the same conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C26",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Recap: Find premises, find conclusion, test support. That’s argument analysis."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C27",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which best distinguishes an explanation?",
          "options": [
            "Gives reasons to believe",
            "Gives reasons why something happened"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.2-C28",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Every argument has exactly two premises.",
          "answer": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "1.3",
      "title": "Premises",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": "1.3-C01",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Welcome to **Premises** — the reasons supporting a conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C02",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "A **premise** provides evidence or reasons."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C03",
          "type": "fill",
          "prompt": "A premise provides ______ for a conclusion.",
          "answer": "support"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C04",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Identify the premise:",
          "options": [
            "Therefore, Socrates is mortal.",
            "All humans are mortal.",
            "Thus, Socrates is human."
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C05",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Premise indicators: 'because', 'since', 'for', 'given that'."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C06",
          "type": "match_pairs",
          "prompt": "Match to role.",
          "left": [
            "because",
            "given that",
            "therefore"
          ],
          "right": [
            "premise",
            "premise",
            "conclusion"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C07",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Evidence can be statistical, testimony, or observation.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C08",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Check premise truth, relevance, and sufficiency."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C09",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which premise is **irrelevant**?",
          "options": [
            "Smoking causes cancer; so taxes reduce smoking.",
            "Smoking causes cancer; so exercise daily."
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C10",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Avoid hidden assumptions: make background claims explicit."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C11",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Independent vs. dependent premises:\n- Independent: each supports the conclusion alone.\n- Dependent: need each other."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C12",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "If removing P1 ruins P2’s usefulness, they were:",
          "options": [
            "Independent",
            "Dependent"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C13",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Dependent premises often appear with 'and'/'together'.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C14",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Premises must be charitable but not stronger than speaker intended."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C15",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which is overly strong?",
          "options": [
            "Some dogs bark.",
            "All dogs bark."
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C16",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Seek the weakest sufficient premise set (no unnecessary assumptions)."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C17",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Classify as Relevant/Irrelevant.",
          "items": [
            "This medicine reduces fever; so it helps flu.",
            "My friend likes it; so it cures flu."
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Relevant",
            "Irrelevant"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C18",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Quality premises are true (or justified), relevant, and jointly sufficient."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C19",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Recap: identify indicators, test relevance, reveal hidden assumptions."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C20",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Premise quality checklist includes:",
          "options": [
            "Truth, relevance, sufficiency",
            "Length, style, humor"
          ],
          "answer": 0
        },
        {
          "id": "1.3-C21",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Premises are optional in arguments.",
          "answer": false
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "1.4",
      "title": "Conclusions",
      "cards": [
        {
          "id": "1.4-C01",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Welcome to **Conclusions** — what the argument tries to establish."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C02",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "A **conclusion** is supported by premises and often signaled by 'therefore', 'so', 'thus'."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C03",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which is the conclusion?",
          "options": [
            "Because the team trained hard",
            "Therefore, the team will win.",
            "Since the coach is experienced"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C04",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "A conclusion can appear at the beginning, middle, or end.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C05",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Ask: 'What is the author trying to get me to believe?'"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C06",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Choose the conclusion:",
          "options": [
            "It rained last night.",
            "The ground is wet, so it rained.",
            "The ground is wet."
          ],
          "answer": 2
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C07",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Beware of conclusion **signpost decoys** — not every 'so' marks a conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C08",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Find the conclusion:\n'Every exam was tough. Therefore, average scores will be low.'",
          "options": [
            "Every exam was tough.",
            "Average scores will be low."
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C09",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Main vs. intermediate conclusions: chains of reasoning can have both."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C10",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "An intermediate conclusion also functions as a premise for another step.",
          "answer": true
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C11",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Standardizing arguments clarifies the main conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C12",
          "type": "fill",
          "prompt": "The conclusion is what the argument attempts to ______.",
          "answer": "prove"
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C13",
          "type": "classify",
          "prompt": "Mark each as Premise or Conclusion.",
          "items": [
            "All cats are mammals",
            "Therefore, Luna is a mammal",
            "Luna is a cat"
          ],
          "labels": [
            "Premise",
            "Conclusion"
          ]
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C14",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "If multiple conclusions appear, choose the claim that best explains why the others were offered."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C15",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Which is likely the **main** conclusion?",
          "options": [
            "We should exercise more.",
            "Exercise improves mood.",
            "Exercise reduces disease risk."
          ],
          "answer": 0
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C16",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "The main conclusion is always the last sentence.",
          "answer": false
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C17",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Signal words help, but **role** in reasoning decides the conclusion."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C18",
          "type": "info",
          "content": "Recap: Identify what’s being supported; separate main from intermediate conclusions."
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C19",
          "type": "mcq",
          "prompt": "Best test for the conclusion:",
          "options": [
            "Which sentence is shortest?",
            "Which claim the premises are trying to support?"
          ],
          "answer": 1
        },
        {
          "id": "1.4-C20",
          "type": "tf",
          "prompt": "Conclusions never act as premises.",
          "answer": false
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}